Signed off by client. Closing on Girdler, 1449, quarter century. Sec, sec. It’s yours! 

I’m going to run the numbers, see how it goes. Sec, sec.

Ah.

That wasn’t the best call.

The Girdler’s Company had a small spike at the start of your investment, Royal Charter as predicted, growing business for a few decades and the residencies within grew in value. More developments kept the building prime through the 1500s. But there’s turbulence in the third quartile of the 1600s. 

Deary me.

The Fire of London in 1666 caused serious damage. All that refurb gone to waste. I can see they’ve even added an engraving: it’s a pity you missed it.

It’s a shame you didn’t go for the Armourer’s. They grew, also got Charter, but their building somehow avoided the fire. Ah, the gift of hindsight. If we cared too much about it, we wouldn’t be in this game.

I reshuffled some of your assets to absorb as much loss as possible, but I think our  best bet is to turn more of the space into rental homes. If you can lease 10 more rooms for a decade, I think we can swallow it.

But we need to give the building a more residential feel. I’m not sure how to do that. I wonder which buildings around here were designed for residents. You can think about it, or have your people think about it, en route. There’s another opportunity I need you to see.

